<h1 class=3D"center">Polar and Cartesian Coordinates</h1>=20


<div class=3D"center"><b>... and how to convert between them.</b></div>

<div class=3D"center"><i>In a hurry? Read the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsi=
sfun.com/polar-cartesian-coordinates.html#summary">Summary</a>. But please =
read why first:</i>

</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>To pinpoint where we are on a map or graph there are two main systems:</=
p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20

<h3>Cartesian Coordinates</h3>=20

<p>Using <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/cartesian-coordinates.h=
tml">Cartesian Coordinates</a> we mark a point by <b>how far along</b> and =
<b>how far up</b> it is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
coordinates-cartesian.svg" alt=3D"coordinates cartesian (12,5)" height=3D"2=
32" width=3D"348"></p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"center80">=20

<h3>Polar Coordinates</h3>=20

<p>Using <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/polar-coordinates.h=
tml">Polar Coordinates</a> we mark a point by <b>how far away</b>, and <b>w=
hat angle</b> it is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/images/=
coordinates-polar.svg" alt=3D"coordinates polar 13 at 22.6 degrees" height=
=3D"232" width=3D"348"></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Converting</h2>=20

<p>To convert from one to the other we will use this triangle:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/coordin=
ates-triangle.gif" alt=3D"coordinates triangle" height=3D"180" width=3D"310=
"></div><br>



<h2>To Convert from Cartesian to Polar</h2>=20

<p>When we know a point in Cartesian Coordinates (x,y) and we want it in Po=
lar Coordinates (r,<i>=CE=B8</i>) we <b>solve a right triangle with two kno=
wn sides</b>.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3 class=3D"larger">Example: What is (12,5) in Polar Coordinates?</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/coordina=
tes-to-polar.gif" alt=3D"coordinates to polar" height=3D"180" width=3D"310"=
></p>=20
	<p>Use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/pythagoras.html">Pythagoras T=
heorem</a> to find the long side (the hypotenuse):</p>=20
	<div class=3D"so">r<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> 12<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup=
></div>

<div class=3D"so">r <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A (12<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup>)=
</div>

<div class=3D"so">r <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A (144 + 25)</div>

<div class=3D"so">r <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A (169)=3D <b>13</b></div>

<p>Use the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sine-cosine-tangent.html">=
Tangent Function</a> to find the angle:</p>=20
<div class=3D"so">tan( <i>=CE=B8</i> ) <em>=3D</em> 5 / 12</div>

<div class=3D"so"><i>=CE=B8</i> <em>=3D</em> tan<sup>-1 </sup>( 5 / 12 ) <e=
m>=3D</em> <b>22,6=C2=B0</b> (to one decimal)</div>

<p class=3D"larger"><b>Answer</b>: the point (12,5) is <b>(13, 22,6=C2=B0)<=
/b> in Polar Coordinates.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"def">=20
<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/image=
s/calculator-sin-cos-tan.jpg" alt=3D"calculator-sin-cos-tan" height=3D"75" =
width=3D"118"></div>

<h3>What is <b>tan<sup>-1</sup></b> ?</h3>=20

<p class=3D"large">It is the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/=
trig-inverse-sin-cos-tan.html">Inverse Tangent Function</a>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt"><b>Tangent</b> </span><span class=3D=
"rt">takes an angle and gives a ratio (like <span class=3D"intbl"><em>5</em=
><strong>12</strong></span>)</span><span class=3D"lt"><b>Inverse Tangent</b=
> </span><span class=3D"rt">takes a ratio and gives an angle (like 22,6=C2=
=B0)</span></div>


</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"fun">=20
<p class=3D"larger"><b>Summary</b>: to convert from Cartesian Coordinates (=
x,y) to Polar Coordinates (r,=CE=B8):</p>=20
<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li><b class=3D"center">r <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A ( x<sup>2</sup> + y<sup>2=
 </sup>)</b></li>=20
	<li><b class=3D"center"><i>=CE=B8</i> <em>=3D</em> tan<sup>-1 </sup>( y / =
x )</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>
<p>Note: Calculators may give the wrong value of <b>tan<sup>-1 </sup>()</b>=
 when x or y are negative, see below for more.</p>=20


<h2>To Convert from Polar to Cartesian</h2>=20

<p>When we know a point in Polar Coordinates (r, <i>=CE=B8</i>), and we wan=
t it in Cartesian Coordinates (x,y) we <b>solve a right triangle with a kno=
wn long side and angle</b>:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is (13, 22,6=C2=B0) in Cartesian Coordinates?</h3>=20

	<div class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/coordi=
nates-to-cartesian.gif" alt=3D"to cartesian coordinates" height=3D"180" wid=
th=3D"310"></div>
<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfu=
n.com/sine-cosine-tangent.html">Cosine</a> for x:</span><span class=3D"rt">=
cos( 22,6=C2=B0 ) <em>=3D</em> x / 13</span> <span class=3D"lt">Rearrange a=
nd solve:</span><span class=3D"rt">x <em>=3D</em> 13 =C3=97 cos( 22,6=C2=B0=
 )</span><span class=3D"lt"></span><span class=3D"rt">x <em>=3D</em> 13 =C3=
=97 0,923</span><span class=3D"lt"></span><span class=3D"rt">x <em>=3D</em>=
 <b>12,002...</b></span>
</div>=20


<div class=3D"two"> <span class=3D"lt">Use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfu=
n.com/sine-cosine-tangent.html">Sine</a> for y:</span><span class=3D"rt">si=
n( 22,6=C2=B0 ) <em>=3D</em> y / 13</span> <span class=3D"lt">Rearrange and=
 solve:</span><span class=3D"rt">y <em>=3D</em> 13 =C3=97 sin( 22,6=C2=B0 )=
</span><span class=3D"lt"></span><span class=3D"rt">y <em>=3D</em> 13 =C3=
=97 0,391</span><span class=3D"lt"></span><span class=3D"rt">y <em>=3D</em>=
 <b>4,996...</b></span></div>


<p class=3D"large">Answer: the point (13, 22,6=C2=B0) is <i>almost exactly<=
/i> <b>(12, 5)</b> in Cartesian Coordinates.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"def">=20
<div class=3D"large">To convert from Polar Coordinates (r,<i>=CE=B8</i>) to=
 Cartesian Coordinates (x,y):</div>
<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li><b class=3D"center">x <em>=3D</em> r</b> =C3=97 <b>cos( <i>=CE=B8</i> =
)</b></li>=20
	<li><b class=3D"center">y <em>=3D</em> r</b> =C3=97 <b>sin(<i> =CE=B8</i> =
)</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>

<h3>How to Remember Which is Which?</h3>=20

<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p class=3D"center"><b>(x,y) is alphabetical,<br>
<b>(cos,sin)</b> is also alphabetical</b></p>=20
</div>
<p>Also <i><b>"y and sine rhyme"</b></i> (try saying it!)</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p>And in JavaScript (if you like coding):</p>=20
<pre>function toCartesian(r, angle) {
			let x <em>=3D</em> r * Math.cos(angle)
			let y <em>=3D</em> r * Math.sin(angle)
			return [x, y]
		}	</pre>=20
</div>


<h2>But What About Negative Values of X and Y?</h2>=20

<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/c=
artesian-quadrants.gif" alt=3D"Quadrants" height=3D"191" width=3D"250"></di=
v>

<h3>Four Quadrants</h3>=20

<p>When we include negative values, the x and y axes divide the<br>
space up into 4 pieces:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><b>Quadrants I, II, III</b> and<b> IV</b></p>=20
<p><i>(They are numbered in a counter-clockwise direction)</i></p>=20
<p>When converting from <span class=3D"larger">Polar to Cartesian</span> co=
ordinates it all works out nicely:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is (12, 195=C2=B0) in Cartesian coordinates?</h3>=20

	<p>r <em>=3D</em> 12 and =CE=B8 <em>=3D</em> 195=C2=B0</p>=20
	<ul class=3D"dart">=20
		<li>x <em>=3D</em> 12 =C3=97 cos(195=C2=B0)<br>
x <em>=3D</em> 12 =C3=97 =E2=88=920,9659...<br>
x <em>=3D</em> <b>=E2=88=9211,59</b> to 2 decimal places</li>=20
		<li>y&nbsp;=3D 12 =C3=97 sin(195=C2=B0)<br>
y <em>=3D</em> 12 =C3=97 =E2=88=920,2588...<br>
y <em>=3D</em> <b>=E2=88=923,11</b> to 2 decimal places</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So the point is at<b> (=E2=88=9211,59, =E2=88=923,11)</b>, which is in =
Quadrant III</p>=20
	</div>
<p>But when converting from <span class=3D"larger">Cartesian to Polar</span=
> coordinates ...</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">... the calculator can give the <b>wrong value o=
f tan<sup>-1</sup></b></p>=20
<p>It all depends what Quadrant the point is in! Use this to fix things:</p=
>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table class=3D"center" style=3D"border-collapse: separate; border-spacing=
: 2px;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center;">Quadrant</th>
			<th scope=3D"col" style=3D"text-align: center;"><b>Value of tan<sup>-1</=
sup></b></th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: center;">I</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align: center;">Use the calculator value</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: center;">II</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align: center;">Add 180=C2=B0 to the calculator value<=
/td>
